{"$ambrosia":"aero:interactive:9417ac60-5f60-11ea-8e69-affb2224d7e8:*","$id":"0a3d5c70-44e0-11ed-87ef-91ce182ef09f","$workspaceId":"7fff47c0-44d6-11ed-bcef-d5307f42495c","$projectId":"86cb0040-44df-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca","annotations":[],"configSchemaVersion":"/pluginGenericSchema/v1","config":{"stage":{"sections":[{"rowsAreFullWidth":false,"backgroundImageUrl":"","rows":[{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"heading-two","ref":"97c0a1cd-9e58-42d3-9a9d-315b327d779a","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Optimal Dividend Policy with Taxes","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"9cd325ce-2811-4e8a-bedd-7dbde2e59908"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"ddc7d168-9c00-4f91-8226-00e36b98814b","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"When the tax rate on dividends exceeds the tax rate on capital gains, shareholders will pay lower taxes if a firm uses share repurchases for all payouts rather than dividends. This tax savings will increase the value of a firm that uses share repurchases rather than dividends. We can also express the tax savings in terms of a firm’s equity cost of capital. Firms that use dividends will have to pay a higher pretax return (and thus a higher equity cost of capital) to offer their investors the same after-tax return as firms that use share repurchases. As a result, the optimal dividend policy when the dividend tax rate exceeds the capital gain tax rate is to ","marks":[]},{"object":"text","text":"pay no dividends at all","marks":[{"type":"italic"}]},{"object":"text","text":".","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"7e8d69bb-2148-422a-af64-a78154779c6c"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"heading-three","ref":"1f61ff5d-1ecf-429c-9cf1-9edae5e49e5e","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Dividends in Practice","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"1e9b45a2-88b3-4ed8-9bbd-1ee0fe4b8290"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"06e81f63-1fc1-4f52-9def-4e6661437b11","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"While firms do still pay dividends, substantial evidence shows that many firms have recognized their tax disadvantage. For example, prior to 1980, most firms used dividends exclusively to distribute cash to shareholders (see ","marks":[]},{"object":"inline","type":"reference-link","ref":"66942392-5536-4f84-b63c-39b9b697a8b8","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Figure 17.5","marks":[]}],"data":{"reference":"7fdf62b0-44e1-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca"}},{"object":"text","text":"). But by 2000, only about 20% of firms relied exclusively on dividends. Starting in the early 2000s, this trend has partially reversed. By 2015 the fraction of firms that relied exclusively on dividends rose to about 40%, most likely driven by the Bush administration’s dramatic lowering of the dividend tax rate in 2003 (see ","marks":[]},{"object":"inline","type":"reference-link","ref":"ad2859ff-1056-4b2e-bafa-17d69fed53d7","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Table 17.2","marks":[]}],"data":{"reference":"7bb6a090-44e1-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca"}},{"object":"text","text":"). A relatively stable 30% of all firms (and more than half of firms making payouts to shareholders) used share repurchases exclusively or in combination with dividends.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"e976c5e4-047c-46f4-9b84-d363b00db87e"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-image","config":{"url":{"$ambrosia":"aero:asset:upload","urn":"urn:aero:ca6eb750-44e0-11ed-bcef-d5307f42495c","asset":{"urn":"urn:aero:ca6eb750-44e0-11ed-bcef-d5307f42495c","asset":{"assetProvider":"ALFRESCO","id":"ca6eb750-44e0-11ed-bcef-d5307f42495c","assetMediaType":"image","assetVisibility":"GLOBAL","ownerId":"e88133a0-8dc4-11eb-964e-4d7e264c9958","subscriptionId":"f0afd4d0-d2ff-11ea-9998-d57e1e28aca1","alfrescoId":"250958fd-2240-4d3e-ae5d-cffc4b2db89a","name":"FG_17_005.jpg","version":"2.0","lastModifiedDate":1664998398,"lastSyncDate":1665085933},"source":{"small":{"width":432,"url":"https://assets-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/ca6eb750-44e0-11ed-bcef-d5307f42495c/small/c722b7265bc08b1955971bb9e13d48be.jpeg","height":300},"original":{"width":864,"url":"https://assets-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/ca6eb750-44e0-11ed-bcef-d5307f42495c/medium/c722b7265bc08b1955971bb9e13d48be.jpeg","height":600},"medium":{"width":864,"url":"https://assets-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/ca6eb750-44e0-11ed-bcef-d5307f42495c/medium/c722b7265bc08b1955971bb9e13d48be.jpeg","height":600},"thumb":{"width":216,"url":"https://assets-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/ca6eb750-44e0-11ed-bcef-d5307f42495c/thumb/c722b7265bc08b1955971bb9e13d48be.jpeg","height":150}},"metadata":{"altText":"","workURN":"","caption":"<p>This figure shows the percentage of U.S. firms making payouts to shareholders. The shaded regions show the firms that used dividends exclusively (<em>blue</em>), repurchases exclusively (<em>green</em>), or both (<em>red</em>&#x2009;). Because firms that repurchase shares do not usually do so every year, we classify a firm as using repurchases if it repurchased that year or the previous year. Note that after steadily declining for more than 20&#xA0;years, dividend use has been on the rise since 2000. However, as <a class=\"xref\" href=\"m166_ch17lev1sec3.xhtml#x0278\">Figure 17.6</a> shows, repurchases now account for the largest part of the total value of distributions.</p>","alfrescoPath":"bronte-e2e-testing-qaint/documentLibrary/BV E2E Test/[10-05-2022] Berk","originalAssetName":"FG_17_005.jpg","longDesc":"","height":"555"}}},"alt":"","caption":"<p>This figure shows the percentage of U.S. firms making payouts to shareholders. The shaded regions show the firms that used dividends exclusively (<em>blue</em>), repurchases exclusively (<em>green</em>), or both (<em>red</em>&#x2009;). Because firms that repurchase shares do not usually do so every year, we classify a firm as using repurchases if it repurchased that year or the previous year. Note that after steadily declining for more than 20&#xA0;years, dividend use has been on the rise since 2000. However, as <a class=\"xref\" href=\"m166_ch17lev1sec3.xhtml#x0278\">Figure 17.6</a> shows, repurchases now account for the largest part of the total value of distributions.</p>","layout":{"captionPosition":"Below"},"credit":"<p><em>Source</em>&#x200A;: Compustat.</p>","activityLabel":"Figure 17.5","activityTitle":"The Rise of Repurchases"},"height":555,"ref":"54a08e77-a06f-4b6f-a4b4-118569dc0471"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"923faaf6-72de-4e66-b013-81e225957650","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"We see a more dramatic trend if we consider the relative magnitudes of both forms of corporate payouts. ","marks":[]},{"object":"inline","type":"reference-link","ref":"2e19befe-de64-45e8-abea-2a43c34919d4","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Figure 17.6","marks":[]}],"data":{"reference":"7febe5d0-44e1-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca"}},{"object":"text","text":" shows the relative importance of share repurchases as a proportion of total payouts to shareholders. Although dividends accounted for more than 80% of corporate payouts until the early 1980s when the SEC issued guidance allowing open-market repurchases, the importance of share repurchases grew dramatically in the mid-1980s. Repurchase activity slows during recessions (see 1990–1991, 2001–2002, and 2009). This fact highlights the flexibility companies have to adjust repurchase payouts as their profits fluctuate. At the same time, there is a strong expectation that companies will maintain dividend payouts unless they are near distress. Partly due to this flexibility and the tax advantages, by the end of the 1990s distributions through repurchasing surpassed those through dividends.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"3570f592-cb5d-4977-9031-2df3e3e02509"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-image","config":{"url":{"$ambrosia":"aero:asset:upload","urn":"urn:aero:caab9940-44e0-11ed-82a0-5b736ba8ac7f","asset":{"urn":"urn:aero:caab9940-44e0-11ed-82a0-5b736ba8ac7f","asset":{"assetProvider":"ALFRESCO","id":"caab9940-44e0-11ed-82a0-5b736ba8ac7f","assetMediaType":"image","assetVisibility":"GLOBAL","ownerId":"e88133a0-8dc4-11eb-964e-4d7e264c9958","subscriptionId":"f0afd4d0-d2ff-11ea-9998-d57e1e28aca1","alfrescoId":"23b1708a-c129-49a6-8a9a-c95467dd2cfa","name":"FG_17_006.jpg","version":"2.0","lastModifiedDate":1664998392,"lastSyncDate":1665085925},"source":{"small":{"width":511,"url":"https://assets-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/caab9940-44e0-11ed-82a0-5b736ba8ac7f/small/3d126adcc75ab9b220260f569853b7de.jpeg","height":300},"original":{"width":1022,"url":"https://assets-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/caab9940-44e0-11ed-82a0-5b736ba8ac7f/medium/3d126adcc75ab9b220260f569853b7de.jpeg","height":600},"medium":{"width":1022,"url":"https://assets-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/caab9940-44e0-11ed-82a0-5b736ba8ac7f/medium/3d126adcc75ab9b220260f569853b7de.jpeg","height":600},"thumb":{"width":255,"url":"https://assets-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/caab9940-44e0-11ed-82a0-5b736ba8ac7f/thumb/3d126adcc75ab9b220260f569853b7de.jpeg","height":150}},"metadata":{"altText":"","workURN":"","caption":"<p>This figure shows the value of share repurchases as a percentage of total payouts to shareholders (dividends and repurchases). Although initially small, the total dollar amount of share repurchases has grown faster than dividends, so that by the late 1990s share repurchases surpassed dividends to become the largest form of corporate payouts for U.S. industrial firms.</p>","alfrescoPath":"bronte-e2e-testing-qaint/documentLibrary/BV E2E Test/[10-05-2022] Berk","originalAssetName":"FG_17_006.jpg","longDesc":"","height":"470"}}},"alt":"","caption":"<p>This figure shows the value of share repurchases as a percentage of total payouts to shareholders (dividends and repurchases). Although initially small, the total dollar amount of share repurchases has grown faster than dividends, so that by the late 1990s share repurchases surpassed dividends to become the largest form of corporate payouts for U.S. industrial firms.</p>","layout":{"captionPosition":"Below"},"credit":"<p><em>Source</em>&#x200A;: Compustat/CRSP data for U.S. firms, excluding financial firms and utilities.</p>","activityLabel":"Figure 17.6","activityTitle":"The Changing Composition of Shareholder Payouts"},"height":470,"ref":"749003c4-97ba-4bfd-bac0-e2530bebcbfd"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"70697c8c-ffcd-4e5e-8d3a-4e9089fc916f","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"While this evidence is indicative of the growing importance of share repurchases as a part of firms’ payout policies, it also shows that dividends remain a key form of payouts to shareholders. The fact that firms continue to issue dividends despite their tax disadvantage is often referred to as the ","marks":[]},{"data":{"ref":"ca5b01fd-8120-4487-81d0-1e38022d268a","stage":{"ref":"ff07a60b-3e2d-4e05-b3af-f5001509f415","sections":[{"ref":"a5045d9f-7070-41dc-8575-79f651fecf2c","rows":[{"ref":"b3e95dc0-b0e4-4ed7-b2b4-90642cdb767a","columns":[{"ref":"4e982507-6702-4ae8-83fe-929f332d69df","stageElements":[{"ref":"9481ac69-2a4d-4539-b774-2cb71c173f0b","type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"button","ref":"d3ca47a2-c19c-4d29-9e03-c901fce05045","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"0a97d8f7-67c0-4f0d-8cef-4315f47bb228","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"When firms continue to issue dividends despite their tax disadvantage.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"data":{}}]}}}]}]}]}]}},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"dividend puzzle","marks":[]}],"object":"inline","type":"key-term","ref":"301b3d06-a2ed-4af2-b143-f14d4549beff"},{"object":"text","text":".","marks":[]},{"data":{"ref":"f35cdabb-11bc-44e1-846d-3fb01f0cf12f","stage":{"ref":"50b5407a-9f85-4434-8098-572ffb058cec","sections":[{"ref":"1697a721-f005-4d40-8ef7-db6293dd75f4","rows":[{"ref":"49f3271d-ebd8-48d0-ac95-0fcbc2b3e017","columns":[{"ref":"ba77d6f6-8e28-46de-9817-4576089f3093","stageElements":[{"ref":"69caac3a-c14a-4f24-a704-4ba86369f6a9","type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"button","ref":"74fb40d0-fa0c-4646-b59a-67479bf60da9","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"bd825b77-1e30-426b-8e01-981326bcb04d","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"See F. Black, “The Dividend Puzzle,” ","marks":[]},{"object":"text","text":"Journal of Portfolio Management","marks":[{"type":"italic"}]},{"object":"text","text":" 2 (1976): 5–8.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"data":{}}]}}}]}]}]}]}},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"5","marks":[]}],"object":"inline","type":"footnote","ref":"aeda3761-e328-4206-9b6b-8e9f8c5dd448"},{"object":"text","text":" ","marks":[]},{"object":"inline","type":"reference-link","ref":"bb2f52bf-01cd-4c12-99ca-e090f26b7b93","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Table 17.3","marks":[]}],"data":{"reference":"80005830-44e1-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca"}},{"object":"text","text":" summarizes dividends versus repurchases, highlighting the differences between the two ways to distribute cash to shareholders. In the next section, we consider some factors that may mitigate this tax disadvantage. In ","marks":[]},{"object":"inline","type":"reference-link","ref":"7d8e3d12-170e-4269-8bdf-f01b12cd2b35","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Section 17.5","marks":[]}],"data":{"reference":"8010fa00-44e1-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca"}},{"object":"text","text":", we examine alternative motivations for using dividends based on differences in information between managers and investors.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"86f35aa4-71a9-4ad6-baac-df34cdbd0583"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-table","config":{"activityLabel":"Table 17.3","instructions":"","tableCaptionText":"","activityTitle":"Summary of Dividends Versus Repurchases","tableTitle":"","captions":"","credit":""},"value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"data":{"id":"ch17table03"},"nodes":[{"data":{},"nodes":[{"data":{},"nodes":[{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[],"object":"block","type":"table-header","ref":"ba30ead8-d2ab-4c15-ab65-93483e246d79"},{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Dividends","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"object":"block","type":"table-header","ref":"1bd1c508-1429-4e4d-98e8-9dc7ceba41b2"},{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Share Repurchases","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"object":"block","type":"table-header","ref":"925552a5-782e-490c-867c-b86083898bb4"}],"object":"block","type":"table-row","ref":"2114e0fe-f444-44cf-ae96-fcf66e0b913a"}],"object":"block","type":"table-head","ref":"2929bf39-656b-42ea-98ec-68a5acdb84b8"},{"data":{},"nodes":[{"data":{},"nodes":[{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"How cash is distributed to shareholders","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"object":"block","type":"table-data","ref":"735d8445-fef9-45a9-a75b-8e7a699aa038"},{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Cash payment made on a per-share basis to all shareholders","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"object":"block","type":"table-data","ref":"fbe89fe8-1cf3-4969-b03d-94dd5bd49d52"},{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Shares are bought back from some shareholders","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"object":"block","type":"table-data","ref":"74038f1e-1c12-4a14-b42e-2ee0405f5701"}],"object":"block","type":"table-row","ref":"80d93ab1-07c1-4e16-ad8e-5c446873d01a"},{"data":{},"nodes":[{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Participation","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"object":"block","type":"table-data","ref":"e5ee24f9-7560-4c18-a726-4473db58c158"},{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Involuntary (everyone with a share receives a dividend)","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"object":"block","type":"table-data","ref":"9ff91172-7e9a-4422-99ae-10f48ad46dad"},{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Voluntary (shareholders choose whether to sell their shares)","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"object":"block","type":"table-data","ref":"159cee09-c859-4faa-b742-fe0e138d1f2b"}],"object":"block","type":"table-row","ref":"a3d8f71f-181f-4257-a557-b1d68770e7c7"},{"data":{},"nodes":[{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Taxation for ordinary investors","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"object":"block","type":"table-data","ref":"bb441587-06e4-43d9-b5eb-0f5a8c5ab05d"},{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Generally taxed as ordinary income, but taxed a